results.title: FDOT Source Book Special Edition 2020
results.description:
2020 witnessed profound changes in how much people move around, their means of transportation as well as land use and activity patterns.

This interactive dashboard provides both a snapshot and detailed information of Florida’s multimodal mobility and safety performance in 2020 as compared to previous years. Users can drill down the data at the statewide as well as District level. This dashboard provides mobility and safety performance measures below within the timeframe between 2017 to 2020:

Crashes data from the University of Florida Signal Four Analytics

Auto Travel Speed data from the National Performance Management Research Data Set (NPMRDS) data via Regional Integrated Transportation Information System (RITIS)

Auto Volumes data from the FDOT Transportation Data & Analytics Office (TDA)

Freight Activity data from the FDOT Transportation Data & Analytics Office (TDA)

Transit Ridership data from the Federal Transit Administration (FTA) – The National Transit Database (NTD)

Air Travel data from the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)

Seaport Tonnage data from the Information Handling Services (IHS) Markit The Port Import/ Export Reporting Service (PIERS)

Fuel Consumption data from the Florida Department of Revenue (DOR)

Air Pollution data from the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) air data

Unemployment Rate data from the Florida Department of Economic Opportunity (DEO)

For any additional information, please contact the Forecasting and Trends Office (FTO) at 850-414-5396.
results.snippet: Information on mobility and safety performance in Florida for 2020 as compared to earlier years.
results.accessInformation: Signal Four Analytics, NPMRDS, RITIS, FDOT TDA, FTA, NTD, FAA, IHS Markit PIERS, DOR, EPA, DEO.

results.title: Urban Boundary and Functional Classification Update Process
results.description:
Urban Areas represent densely developed areas based on population density. The Census revises these urban areas every 10 years based on population counts from the decennial census. Once the Census Bureau has designated new urban areas, the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) gives state DOTs the opportunity to adjust and revise these boundaries to be more consistent with transportation planning needs. Along with Urban Boundary designation, FHWA also recommends that states review the functional classification of their roadway system every 10 years, and that the review be completed within three years of approval by FHWA of the adjusted urban boundaries.

This website will host the District Urban Boundary and Functional Classification data to be adjusted.

Point of Contact: Jerry Scott and Joel Worrell.
results.snippet: On a decennial basis (every 10 years) following every Census, FDOT in coordination with FHWA and local partners are required to update Urban Boundary and Functional Classification for the State of Florida.

results.title: Crawford County Comprehensive Plan
results.description:
This Arc Hub site is the project website for Crawford County's 2024 Comprehensive Plan update and development of a model for subdivision and land development administration. The website utilizes imagery, mapping, applications, hyperlinks, and text to convey the various stages of the project to an audience that will evolve from potential consultants to specific stakeholder segments to the general public. In other words, this website was initially used for solicitation of professional services to provide expert insight during the project and will be changed to accommodate later stages of the project.

This site will be a resource for the Crawford County Planning Commission, Planning Office, Comprehensive Plan Steering Committee, and project consultant.
results.snippet: Project website for 2024 comprehensive plan update for Crawford County.

results.title: OneMap
results.description:
Geospatial collaboratives are inherently multi-organizational. When organizations integrate their geospatial infrastructure, they can quickly and easily interconnect across borders, jurisdictions, and sectors to address shared challenges. The term ‘OneMap’ is a placeholder for your community GIS branding. Whether you call your initiative a Spatial Data Infrastructure (SDI), Open Data, Digital Twin, Knowledge Infrastructure, Digital Ecosystem, or otherwise, collaboration is key.

  • View Hub Examples
  • Explore the Essential Guides for 'OneMap' Administrators

The 'OneMap' concept is multi-organizational. The website is designed to help communities of practice integrate your geospatial infrastructure (modern SDI). Use it to foster sharing of data among partners; provide a focus on thematic topics and foundational data; and reciprocate value with your contributing partners.

This item is available to ArcGIS Hub Basic and Premium licensed organizations.
results.snippet: The OneMap template can be used to connect multiple organizations to collaborate and share with internal and external stakeholders.
